Let the tens digit of the original number be $x$ and the units digit be $y$. Then, we know that:

\begin{align*}
x+y&=10 \quad\quad\quad \text{(sum of digits is 10)} \\
10y+x &= 3(10x+y)-2 \quad\quad\quad \text{(reversed number is 2 less than 3 times original)}
\end{align*}

Simplifying the second equation, we get:

\begin{align*}
10y+x &= 30x+3y-2 \\
9y-29x &= -2
\end{align*}

Now we have two equations with two variables. We can solve for $x$ in the first equation and substitute into the second equation:

\begin{align*}
x+y&=10 \\
x&=10-y \\
\\
9y-29x &= -2 \\
9y-29(10-y) &= -2 \\
9y-290+29y &= -2 \\
38y &= 288 \\
y &= 8
\end{align*}

So the units digit of the original number is 8. We can substitute this back into the first equation to find the tens digit:

\begin{align*}
x+y &= 10 \\
x+8 &= 10 \\
x &= 2
\end{align*}

Therefore, the original number is $\boxed{28}$.
